==English==
===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/kwɪd/}}
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɪd|-ɪd]]

===Etymology 1===
From Latin [[#Latin|quid]] ‘what, something’, neuter singular of [[quis]] ‘who’.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# The inherent nature of something.
# (''US historical'') A section of the Republican Party between 1805 and 1811 (''from [[tertium quid]]'').

===Etymology 2===
Origin unknown.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|pl='''quid''' ''or (rare)'' '''[[quids]]'''}}

# (''Historical'') A [[sovereign]] or [[guinea]].
#(''UK colloquial'') [[Pound sterling]].
#:''Twenty quid for a sandwich?  You're having a laugh!''
#(''Australian colloquial'') [[pound]] (''before the 1966 currency change'')
#(''Irish colloquial'') [[pound]], [[punt]], [[euro]]

====Synonyms====
*(''pound sterling''):
**(''standard English''): [[pound]], [[pound sterling]]
**(''slang''): [[nicker]], [[sov]]

====Derived terms====
*[[quids in]]

===Etymology 3===
Variant of [[cud]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

#A piece of [[tobacco]] for [[chew]]ing.

